Commit Message:
Initial Commit

This initial commit contains a lot of code, and the majority of it was
simply pulled out of the https://github.com/sallamander/dl-playground
repository in order to build a stand-alone package that included the
Keras-centric training / evaluation code for PyTorch networks.

Major changes / additions added in the initial commit largely reolve around
the addition of the `backend.py` in order to allow for Keras to be used
with a `numpy` backend, rather than requiring tensorflow or some other
backend that would add an additional dependency, or creating a PyTorch
backend, which would be a much larger effort.
Add fit and evaluate methods to Model class

Fix incorrect sample # display in progress bar

The last batch may not necessarily be a complete batch, and the `Model.fit`
was assuming that each batch was a full one, leaving a possibly incorrect
display in the progress bar and possibly incorrect calculations for the last
batch.
Update categorical_accuracy to work for sequences
Move setup.py to the correct place

Add MVP TensorBoard callback

The TensorBoard callback doesn't have all of the functionality that the Keras
version does, but it's a start and will be expanded upon over time.

Expose ktorch-compatible Keras callbacks

Several Keras callbacks work out of the box with the ktorch Model class, and
importing those in the ktorch.callbacks module will make it easier for users
to learn this and use these ktorch-compatible callbacks. In addition, it is
also documented in the ktorch.callbacks docstring.
Update setup.py to include all dependencies
Add model attribute to fix broken ModelCheckpoint callback
Update FileWriter __init__ because of signature changes
Allow initialized optimizer to be passed into Model.compile
Update list of optimizers tested in TestModel.test_compile
Allow initialized loss to be passed into Model.compile
Alter Model integration tests to run on CPU and GPU

Add initial, limited implementation of multi-output training

This commit allows for multi-output training in (very) limited way (at least
compared to what is possible with the Keras Model class). In particular, users
must specify multiple outputs via the `__init__` of the Model class using the
`n_outputs` parameter.  Then, the targets passed to the network must be a list
of torch.Tensor objects whose length matches `n_outputs` passed to the init.
The network passed to the `Model.__init__`, must return `n_outputs` number of
outputs. The objective function will be applied to each pair of (targets,
outputs) and summed with equal weights, and each metric will be applied to each
pair of (targets, outputs). Subsequent commits will make updates and make
extensions to this limited functionality to bring it more in line with what the
Keras Model class offers.

Add ability to specify loss-weights

This commit also includes some cleanup and refactoring of other code in the
Model class, specifically in the `compile`, `train_on_batch, and
`test_on_batch`.
